<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="308" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,331,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,331,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[453,649,331,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" refId="ref14900" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica Part VI Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 447 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
it runs to Group IV couplet 4, but its hypopygium is different from both options. In the key to the males of species from the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney R. H. L." box="[969,1121,367,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref14009" refString="Disney R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8), Royal Entomologicai Society of London, 1 - 155. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631287 X 00115" type="book chapter" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 121 and in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz, H." box="[182,377,403,430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" pagination="465 - 512" refId="ref15017" refString="Schmitz, H. (1958) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region 4 (33) (Lieferung 202). E. Schweizerbartsche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, 465 - 512." type="book chapter" year="1958">Schmitz’s (1958)</bibRefCitation>
key for Abteilung IV Erste Reihe it runs to couplet 18, but in both cases is excluded by its distinctive hypopygium. Likewise in Borgmeier’s (1964b) key Group IV it runs to couplet 20 lead 1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,331,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,475,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">`Description.</emphasis>
Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[528,592,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, with dense but very fine microtrichia. Cheek with 6 robust bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and even more robust. Postpedicels, with a few SPS vesicles (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1162,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation box="[151,220,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, the labella lacking short spinules below. Thorax (
<figureCitation box="[790,858,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) with 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these, mesopleuron with hairs and scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles.Abdominal tergites as 
<figureCitation box="[273,341,619,646]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
. Venter brown, and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[1082,1184,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Figs 6–8</figureCitation>
. Legs brown but front leg more yellowish brown. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[612,682,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisades on segments 1–5 and 5 clearly longer than 4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.78 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur subequal to those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[806,888,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with 7–8 differentiated posterodorsal bristles, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical comb simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1099,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="308">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[1117,1219,763,790]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.14" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" unit="mm" value="1.14">1.14 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.49. Costal ratios 4: 2.3: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[763,863,799,826]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
long. Vein 3 with hair (but only its sockets present on both wings). 2 axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[771,871,835,862]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="2" pageNumber="308" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Halteree brown.
</paragraph>
